<b><i>Table 5</i> – NV Index handles for FDO Credentials</b>

Note that different handle values are used for different key sizes,
the TPM SHALL be provisioned with only one key size for each FDO
parameter. The Device key and its corresponding Device certificate are
stored at the same offset within their respective handle range. 

<div class="informative">

The FDO Certificate index (`0x01D10005`) is listed as optional. In
practice, this index has limited utility:

* The Ownership Voucher is a CBOR-encoded, FDO-specific data
  structure -- not an X.509 certificate. It cannot be processed by
  standard X.509 tooling.
* Ownership Vouchers routinely exceed 1 KB, which exceeds the NV
  storage budget of many TPMs (especially resource-constrained
  models).
* The Ownership Voucher does not contain secret material. Its
  integrity is already guaranteed by its cryptographic signature
  chain. Storing it in TPM NV adds complexity without a corresponding
  security benefit.
* The device can re-obtain the Ownership Voucher at any time by
  re-running TO2. For local caching, the OV MAY be stored on
  non-TPM media (filesystem, flash partition) without compromising
  the TPM's security guarantees for actual secrets.

If this index is used, it SHOULD contain the device's X.509
certificate (e.g., IDevID or LDevID certificate) rather than the
Ownership Voucher. Implementations SHOULD be aware of TPM NV size
constraints when provisioning this index.

</div>



## Authorization for FDO Credentials ## {#Authorization_LABEL}

<div class="informative">

The authorization requirement for FDO keys are:  



* During ROE: no restriction on usage

    FIDO Device Onboard is performed at the beginning of a device’s lifetime, when the operating system of a new device starts for the first time. At this point, the device has only generic content and functions (these are installed only at the end of the onboarding process). The system of the device trusts the TPM on first use. As a consequence, no authorization or a simple authorization (to prevent mistakes) is used. 

* During device operation (in the field): 

    The OS can extract and delete the Ownership Voucher as well as change the Active flag.


    Furthermore, if an IDevID or LDevID is used for the FDO Device Identity key, the access rights of these keys persist. If an FDO Device Identity key is used then it is not accessible from the OS.


The policies and template used to enforce this behavior are defined in Section 7.


